AB  - This article examines how and in which societal and political contexts nationhood is expressed and symbolised in reunified Germany. This 'rediscovery' of nationhood since the 1990s mixes new and old motifs of the cultural repertoire of 'the national' for different purposes. Three main contexts triggered a rediscovery of 'the national' after 1989: reunification, immigration and the retrenchment of the social state. I argue, by analysing ethnographic material and political discourses, that these contexts, on the one hand, rearticulate old forms of ethnic and cultural nationalism and, on the other hand, create new images and symbols of an open civic society and immigration country. There are 'playful' forms, such as campaigns of nation branding, that symbolically include the 'productive' and 'useful' immigrant into the national project. Moreover, such campaigns serve to legitimatise the downsizing of the national state that - according to a neoliberal attitude - relies on a new community spirit of entrepreneurial, 'activated' citizens who 'help themselves'. Thus, focusing on these pluralised renationalisation processes makes evident how polyvalent 'the national' still is. It can be employed by those who attempt to 'reunite' the East and West Germans, by businesses to sell their goods and ideas and by almost any political orientation, be it right-wing or left-wing.
